Alam Sutera, Danamon, Intraco, Medco: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-07-15T02:00:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-15/alam-sutera-danamon-intraco-medco-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are
in parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  rose 0.4 percent to 3,997.64.  Energy companies: Oil futures in  New York  fell 2.4 percent
to $95.69 a barrel in New York yesterday, snapping a two-day
rally. Crude was last at $96.30.  PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), Indonesia’s second-
largest listed oil company, was unchanged at 205 rupiah. PT
Benakat Petroleum Energy (BIPI IJ) was unchanged at 101 rupiah.  PT Alam Sutera Realty (ASRI IJ): The property developer may
spend 100 billion rupiah ($11.7 million) to 200 billion rupiah
to build a theme park in 2012, Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing
Lilia Setiprawarti Sukotjo, a director at the company. Alam
Sutera jumped 6 percent to 355 rupiah.  PT Bank Danamon  Indonesia  (BDMN IJ): The Indonesian lender
controlled by Singapore’s Temasek Holdings Pte and Deutsche Bank
AG said it plans to sell new shares in a rights offer to bolster
capital. Bank Danamon was unchanged at 5,800 rupiah.  PT Intraco Penta (INTA IJ): The company plans to sell 200
billion rupiah to 220 billion rupiah of medium-term notes next
month to fund expansion, Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing
Finance Director Fred Lopez Manibog. Intraco, which trades and
leases heavy equipment, rose 1.4 percent to 730 rupiah.  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ): Indonesia’s
biggest listed oil company will invest $35 million to explore
for geothermal energy in the  Philippines , Asia Pulse  reported ,
citing Budi Basuki, chief executive at a company unit carrying
out the project. Medco was unchanged at 2,300 rupiah.  PT Wintermar Offshore Marine (WINS IJ): The provider of
shipping services obtained a $27 million five-year loan from PT
Bank Mandiri (BMRI IJ) to buy vessels,  Bisnis Indonesia 
reported, citing Pek Swan Layanto, head of Wintermar’s corporate
planning department. Wintermar was unchanged at 330 rupiah and
Mandiri, the nation’s largest bank by assets, advanced 2.6
percent to 7,800 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net  